Here are short speaker bullets for a presentation on GitHub Copilot Skills markdown files:
* GitHub Copilot Skills are reusable markdown-based task guides for specific jobs
* They are best for detailed, task-specific workflows, not always-on repo guidance (GitHub Docs)
* A skill helps Copilot perform specialized work with instructions, scripts, and supporting resources (GitHub Docs)
* Each skill lives in its own folder and is defined by a SKILL.md file (GitHub Docs)
* The skill name and description help Copilot decide when the skill is relevant (GitHub Docs)
* Skills can be triggered automatically when relevant, or invoked manually with a slash command in Copilot CLI (GitHub Docs)
* Skills are useful when a team wants repeatable engineering workflows instead of rewriting the same prompt every time
* For example, a Spring Boot team can create skills for controller generation, test creation, API review, logging checks, or deployment steps
* Skills improve consistency, speed, and reuse across common development tasks
* They help encode team knowledge into a format Copilot can use on demand
* Skills should be focused, practical, and narrow in scope
* If a skill is too broad, too long, or outdated, it becomes less effective
* Best practice: use instructions for always-needed repo rules, and skills for deeper task-specific guidance(GitHub Docs)
* Think of a skill as a reusable expert playbook for one kind of task
* Good skills make Copilot feel more like a specialized teammate, not just a generic code assistant
One-line closing statement:
* GitHub Copilot Skills turn repeatable engineering workflows into reusable markdown playbooks that Copilot can apply when needed
